var definitions = ['<h2>Der Abenteurer geht in die dunkle Höhle.</h2><div><strong>Der</strong> This is the German definite article for masculine singular nouns in the nominative case. It means "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Abenteurer</strong> This is a masculine noun in the singular nominative case. It means "adventurer".</div><div><strong>geht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition that, in this context, means "into". It’s used to indicate movement towards the inside of a place.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the German definite article for feminine singular nouns in the accusative case. It means "the" in English and precedes the noun "Höhle".</div><div><strong>dunkle</strong> This is an adjective in its basic form used here in the accusative case. It means "dark" and agrees with the noun it is describing in gender (feminine), number (singular), and case (accusative).</div><div><strong>Höhle</strong> This is a feminine noun in the singular accusative case. It means "cave".</div>','<h2>Das Auto fährt in die Garage.</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the German definite article for neuter nouns in the nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. It accompanies the noun "Auto" which is a neuter noun.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is the German neuter noun for "car". It’s the subject of the sentence in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>fährt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive". It indicates the action performed by the subject (the car).</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a German preposition that can mean "in" or "into" depending on the case that follows. With the accusative case, as it is used here, it means "into" indicating a direction towards a goal.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the German definite article for feminine nouns in the accusative case, corresponding to "the" in English. It proceeds "Garage" confirming the motion towards the location.</div><div><strong>Garage</strong> This is the German feminine noun for "garage". Its accusative case indicates that it’s the direct object of motion within the sentence.</div>','<h2>Die Erdbeere ist im Korb.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German in the nominative case for feminine singular nouns, meaning "the".</div><div><strong>Erdbeere</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German, meaning "strawberry". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It connects the subject to the predicate of the sentence.</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" (meaning "in" or "inside") and the definite article "dem". In German, "in dem" often contracts to "im". "Dem" is the dative case of the definite article for masculine and neuter nouns; it indicates location here.</div><div><strong>Korb</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in German, meaning "basket". It is the object of the preposition "in" and is in the dative case because of the preposition.</div>','<h2>Der Hund setzt sich auf den Teppich.</h2><div><strong>Der</strong> This is the German definite article for masculine nouns in the nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. It signals that a specific, male-gendered noun is following.</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is a German noun meaning "dog". It is masculine and in the nominative case because it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>setzt sich</strong> This is a reflexive verb construction in present tense. "setzt" is the third-person singular form of "setzen", which means "to sit" or "to set", and "sich" is a reflexive pronoun in accusative case meaning "himself" or "itself". Together, they translate to "sits down" or "settles".</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a German two-way preposition which can mean "on", "onto" or "upon". In this context with the accusative case that follows, it means "onto".</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the German definite article for masculine nouns in the accusative case. It translates as "the" in English and indicates that the noun that follows is the direct object of the verb.</div><div><strong>Teppich</strong> This is a German noun meaning "carpet" or "rug". It is masculine and in the accusative case because it is the object of the preposition "auf".</div>','<h2>Das Buch liegt auf dem Tisch.</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the definite article in German for the neutral noun "Buch" and translates as "the" in English. It indicates that we’re talking about a specific book.</div><div><strong>Buch</strong> This is a neutral noun in German that stands for "book". In the sentence, it’s the subject, the item that is performing the action of being on the table.</div><div><strong>liegt</strong> This word comes from the verb "liegen", which means "to lie" or "to be situated". In this sentence, it’s the third-person singular present tense, indicating the current state of the book.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a two-way preposition in German that can mean "on", "at", "in", or "to", depending on the context. Combined with the article and noun ("dem Tisch"), it denotes the location of the book.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the dative article for masculine and neuter nouns in German. "Tisch" is a masculine noun, and since "auf" requires the dative case in this context (because it’s describing a static location), "dem" is used here to mean "the".</div><div><strong>Tisch</strong> This is a masculine noun in German and it means "table". In the sentence, it’s part of a prepositional phrase indicating the location of the book.</div>','<h2>Der Junge spielt auf dem Hausdach.</h2><div><strong>Der</strong> This is the German definite article for masculine nouns in the nominative case. It is equivalent to "the" in English and is used to specify a particular item that is known to the speaker and listener.</div><div><strong>Junge</strong> This is a German noun meaning "boy". It is in the nominative case and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spielt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". Here, it indicates an ongoing action being performed by the boy.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This German preposition means "on" in English and is used to describe the location where the action of the verb is taking place. Combined with the definite article "dem", it forms a prepositional phrase indicating location.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the German definite article for neuter or masculine nouns in the dative case. It typically follows prepositions like "auf" and indicates an indirect object or location. In this sentence, it is part of the prepositional phrase describing where the boy is playing.</div><div><strong>Hausdach</strong> This is a German noun meaning "roof of a house". It is in the dative case following the preposition "auf", completing the prepositional phrase started by "auf dem". This indicates where the boy is playing.</div>','<h2>Ich hänge ein Bild an die Wand.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hänge</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "hängen", which means "to hang". Here, it indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun "Bild" to indicate that it is a single, non-specific item.</div><div><strong>Bild</strong> This is a neutral noun in German, which means "picture" or "image" in English. It is the direct object of the sentence, the item being acted upon by the verb.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "on", "to", or "at" depending on the context. Here, combined with the accusative case, it means "to" as in attaching something to a surface.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article for feminine or plural nouns in the accusative case in German, which means "the" in English. In this context, it precedes the noun "Wand" to indicate a specific wall.</div><div><strong>Wand</strong> This is a feminine noun in German, which means "wall" in English. It is the indirect object of the sentence, representing the surface to which the picture is being attached.</div>','<h2>Die Mutter setzt sich an das Fenster, um auf ihre Kinder aufzupassen.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article for feminine, nominative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It indicates a specific, singular, feminine noun is being discussed.</div><div><strong>Mutter</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "mother". In the sentence, it’s the subject who is performing the action.</div><div><strong>setzt sich</strong> This is a reflexive verb phrase comprising the verb "setzen" (to set or to put) used with the reflexive pronoun "sich", here meaning "to sit down".</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a two-way preposition in German that can mean "at" or "to", depending on the context. When used with the accusative case, it indicates direction. Here it’s used to indicate the location by the window.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the definite article for neutral, accusative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes and refers to a specific, neutral noun in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Fenster</strong> This is a neutral noun in German that means "window". The action of the mother sitting is directed towards the window.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This conjunction is used to introduce a purpose or to explain the reason why something is done. It is similar to "in order to" in English.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is another versatile preposition in German which can have various meanings depending on the context. Here, it means "to watch over" as part of the phrase "aufpassen auf" (to look after).</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, feminine plural form, meaning "her" and referring to something that belongs to the subject, the mother. It signifies that the children are hers.</div><div><strong>Kinder</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Kind", which means "children". It’s the object of the action "aufpassen", indicating who the mother is looking after.</div><div><strong>aufzupassen</strong> This is an infinitive construct in German, which combines the preposition "auf" with the verb "passen" in its separable prefix form "aufpassen" (to watch over). The use of the infinitive with "um" indicates the purpose of the mother’s action (sitting by the window), which is to watch over her children.</div>','<h2>Ihr tretet an die Tür heran.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>tretet</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "treten", which means "to step" or "to approach". It describes the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This word is a separable prefix that is part of the verb "antreten", which in this case means "to approach" something. In German, some verbs have prefixes that can be separated and placed at the end of the sentence, but here "an" is kept with the verb due to the sentence structure.</div><div><strong>die Tür</strong> This phrase means "the door" in English, with "die" being the feminine definite article and "Tür" the noun for "door".</div><div><strong>heran</strong> This is a direction adverb that means "towards" or "to", and it is emphasizing the direction towards which the subjects are approaching. When combined with "antreten", "heran" completes the idea of moving towards something closely. It is usually placed at the end of the clause or sentence.</div>','<h2>Die Sonne scheint am Himmel.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German, corresponding to "the" in English. It indicates a specific noun and agrees with the feminine singular noun.</div><div><strong>Sonne</strong> This is a feminine singular noun that means "sun" in English. Here, it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>scheint</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "scheinen", which means "to shine" in English. It describes the action the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>am Himmel</strong> This is a prepositional phrase. "am" is a contraction of "an dem", which translates to "on the" or "in the" in English, specifying a location. "Himmel" means "sky", so together, "am Himmel" translates to "in the sky".</div>','<h2>Ich bin an der Universität.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a two-way preposition in German that can mean "at", "on", or "by", depending on the context. Here, it is used to indicate location.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article for feminine singular nouns in the dative case in German. "Universität" is a feminine noun, and since "an" is a two-way preposition that requires the dative case in this context, "der" is used.</div><div><strong>Universität</strong> This is the German noun for "university". It’s a feminine singular noun and in this sentence it’s in the dative case because it follows the preposition "an".</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Wohnen Sie in Rom?</h2><div><strong>Wohnen</strong> This is the second-person plural (or formal "you") present tense form of the verb "wohnen", which means "to live" or "to reside". It’s used here as the main verb of the question.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for either singular or plural addressees, similar to "usted" in Spanish. In this context, it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German which has several meanings, including "in" or "at". It’s used here to indicate location.</div><div><strong>Rom?</strong> This is the German name for the city of Rome, the capital of Italy. Ending the sentence with a question mark indicates that the sentence is a question, asking whether the person lives in Rome.</div>','<h2>Er setzt sich in den Schnee.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German third-person singular masculine pronoun equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>setzt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "setzen", which means "to set" or "to put". In this reflexive form, combined with "sich" it means "sits down".</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun used in German. In this sentence, it refers to the subject "he", modalizing the verb "setzt" to indicate the action is performed on oneself, so "he sits (himself) down".</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German used here to indicate location, equivalent to "in" in English.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the masculine singular accusative definite article in German. It precedes "Schnee", indicating that "snow" is the direct object of the preposition "in".</div><div><strong>Schnee</strong> This is the German word for "snow". It is a masculine singular noun and in this sentence, it is in the accusative case following the preposition "in", describing where "he" is sitting down.</div>','<h2>Es ist niemand in der Wüste.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s often used as a formal subject to start a sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Es" with the rest of the predicate.</div><div><strong>niemand</strong> This means "nobody" or "no one" in English. It is a negative indefinite pronoun used to indicate the absence of people.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition that can have various meanings depending on the context. Here, it is used to indicate location, similar to "in" in English.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article for the feminine singular noun in the dative case in German. Here, it agrees with the following noun "Wüste".</div><div><strong>Wüste</strong> This is a feminine singular noun meaning "desert" in English. The phrase "in der Wüste" means "in the desert".</div>','<h2>Ja, besonders in guter Gesellschaft!</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It is often used to affirm a statement or answer positively to a question.</div><div><strong>besonders</strong> This is an adverb in German, meaning "especially" or "particularly". It is used to emphasize that something stands out among others or in comparison.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German, which can mean "in" or "inside". The preposition "in" is used here to specify the context or location where something is considered particularly good or desirable.</div><div><strong>guter</strong> This is the nominative case of the masculine or neuter singular form of the adjective "gut", which means "good" in English. It agrees with the noun it modifies, which must be either masculine or neuter in singular form.</div><div><strong>Gesellschaft!</strong> This is a feminine noun in German for "company" or "society". It’s in the nominative case and is the thing being described as "good" in this context, typically meaning "presence of other people" or "social gathering".</div>','<h2>Du wohnst in Köln, nicht wahr?</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used in informal settings.</div><div><strong>wohnst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "wohnen", which means "to live" or "to reside". It indicates where the subject resides.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that can be translated to "in" or "at" in English. It is used here to describe the location where the subject lives.</div><div><strong>Köln</strong> This is a proper noun, the name of a city in Germany, known as "Cologne" in English. It is the place being referred to where the subject resides.</div><div><strong>nicht wahr?</strong> This is a German phrase equivalent to "isn’t it?" or "right?" in English. It’s a tag question added to the end of a statement to ask for confirmation.</div>','<h2>Sie würden gerne in München leben.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is a polite form of "you" in German. It can refer to a single person in a formal context, or to several people as a plural form. Here, it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>würden</strong> This is the plural form of the conditional mood of "werden", which means "would" in English. It indicates a non-real or hypothetical situation when used with an infinitive, forming the conditional mood.</div><div><strong>gerne</strong> This is an adverb meaning "gladly" or "with pleasure" in English. It describes an action done willingly or with enjoyment.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition denoting a relationship involving location or place. In this context, it is similar to "in" in English.</div><div><strong>München</strong> This is a proper noun, the German name for Munich, a major city in Germany. Here, it is the location being referred to.</div><div><strong>leben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to live" in German. Combined with "würden", it expresses a hypothetical or desired state of living somewhere.</div>','<h2>Es gibt niemanden in der Bibliothek.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German neutral third-person singular pronoun, similar to "it" in English. It’s often used as an impersonal pronoun to start a sentence, particularly with "geben" to express existence.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give" or "to exist" in this context. It is used to indicate the existence or presence of something or someone.</div><div><strong>niemanden</strong> This is the accusative form of "niemand", which is a negative indefinite pronoun in German meaning "nobody" or "no one". It inflects for case, and here it’s accusative due to its function as the direct object of the verb.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a two-way preposition in German, which, depending on the context, can be translated as "in", "into", or "at". It is followed by the dative case when indicating a location (as it does here), or the accusative case when indicating a direction.</div><div><strong>der Bibliothek</strong> This phrase consists of the article "der" in the dative case, followed by the noun "Bibliothek", which means "library". The dative case is used because the preposition "in" (indicating location) governs the dative in this context.</div>','<h2>Wir haben unser Gepäck in Bayern gelassen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it is used as the auxiliary verb to form the perfect tense.</div><div><strong>unser</strong> This is a possessive adjective in German, equivalent to "our" in English. It indicates possession or association with the subject "wir" (we).</div><div><strong>Gepäck</strong> This is a German noun meaning "luggage" or "baggage". It is the direct object of the sentence, showing what has been left in Bayern.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German indicating location or position. It is similar to the English preposition "in".</div><div><strong>Bayern</strong> This is a proper noun in German, the name of a federal state in Germany, known as Bavaria in English. It is where the subject has left their luggage.</div><div><strong>gelassen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "lassen", which means "to leave". Combined with "haben", it forms the perfect tense of the verb, explaining what action was taken with the luggage.</div>','<h2>Ich werde heute Abend in der Show tanzen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which means "to become". In this context, it is used to form the future tense, indicating an action that will take place.</div><div><strong>heute Abend</strong> This is a German adverbial phrase meaning "this evening" or "tonight". It indicates the time when the action (dancing) will occur.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "in" in English. It precedes a noun phrase and denotes location or inclusion within.</div><div><strong>der Show</strong> This is a noun phrase where "der" is the feminine singular definite article "the", and "Show" means "show" in English, borrowed from English but used in the German context. Together they mean "in the show".</div><div><strong>tanzen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "tanzen", which means "to dance" in English. In this sentence, it is linked with the auxiliary "werde" to denote a future action.</div>','<h2>Ich hatte in der Vergangenheit viel gelitten.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hatte</strong> This is the first-person singular past perfect tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this case, it’s an auxiliary verb used to form the past perfect tense, indicating that the action was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German, which corresponds to "in" in English. It’s used here to indicate a reference point in time.</div><div><strong>der Vergangenheit</strong> These two words together mean "in the past". "Der" is a definite article in the feminine singular form, and "Vergangenheit" is the feminine noun for "past".</div><div><strong>viel</strong> This is an adverb in German, meaning "much" or "a lot". It describes the extent or degree of the suffering mentioned.</div><div><strong>gelitten</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "leiden", which means "to suffer". It’s used here with the auxiliary verb "hatte" to form the past perfect tense.</div>','<h2>Ich auch. Sprechen Sie Deutsch in den USA?</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too". It indicates that the speaker is adding to the previous statement or agrees with it.</div><div><strong>Sprechen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "sprechen", which means "to speak" in German. If it were conjugated to match "Sie", it would be "Sprechen Sie" as a formal question asking "Do you speak?"</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. When beginning with a capital letter, it’s formal address and used here as the subject of a polite question.</div><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This is a noun meaning "German" in English, referring to the German language.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in both German and English and is used here to indicate location or place.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the definite article for masculine or neuter nouns in the plural accusative case in German. "USA" is understood to be plural and treated as a masculine noun in German, thus using "den" instead of "die" which is for feminine or plural nouns in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>USA</strong> This is an acronym standing for "United States of America". It is used the same way in German as it is in English.</div>','<h2>Danke. Haben Sie sie auch in anderen Farben?</h2><div><strong>Danke</strong> This is the German word for "thanks" or "thank you". It’s an expression of gratitude.</div><div><strong>Haben</strong> This is the third-person plural or formal "you" form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this question, it’s addressing someone formally with "Sie".</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for polite address or when speaking to someone you don’t know well.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person feminine or plural pronoun in German, meaning "she" or "they". Here, it likely refers to a plural noun mentioned earlier, such as "shoes" or "dresses" in context, thus meaning "them".</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This German word means "also" or "too". It indicates an addition or alternative to what has been previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "in" or "into" when followed by a dative or accusative object, depending on motion or position.</div><div><strong>anderen</strong> This is the dative plural form of "ander", which means "other". It’s used here to imply "other ones" or "different ones" in the context of colors.</div><div><strong>Farben?</strong> This is the plural form of "Farbe", which means "color" in German. The question is asking about the availability of the object in different colors.</div>','<h2>Er ist den ganzen Tag in schlechter Stimmung gewesen.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. In this sentence, it forms part of the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>den ganzen Tag</strong> This phrase means "the whole day" or "all day" in English. It indicates the duration of the action.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "in" or "into" in English, depending on the context. Here, it indicates the state in which the subject has been.</div><div><strong>schlechter Stimmung</strong> This phrase means "in a bad mood" in English. "Stimmung" is a feminine noun meaning "mood", and "schlechter" is the comparative form of the adjective "schlecht", meaning "bad", used here in the dative case due to the preposition "in".</div><div><strong>gewesen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "sein" (to be) used here to form the present perfect tense in German. It indicates the past state of being.</div>','<h2>Sie hat sich draußen in der Hängematte ausgeruht.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person feminine singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". It’s used here to form the perfect tense in the sentence.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case. It reflects back to the subject, pointing out that the action is being done to herself. In this sentence, it’s part of the reflexive verb "sich ausruhen" which means "to rest".</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This is an adverb meaning "outside". It indicates where the action of resting is taking place.</div><div><strong>in der</strong> This is a combination of a preposition "in" and a definite article "der" in the dative case, which together mean "in the" in English. This prepositional phrase sets up the location where the action is happening.</div><div><strong>Hängematte</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in the dative case, meaning "hammock". It’s the object of the prepositional phrase denoted by "in der", indicating where the subject rested.</div><div><strong>ausgeruht</strong> This is the past participle of the reflexive verb "sich ausruhen", meaning "rested". It’s used with the auxiliary verb "hat" to construct the present perfect tense which describes a past action that is relevant to or affects the present.</div>','<h2>Ich werde in der Achterbahn nicht schreien.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense form of the verb "werden", which means "to become". Here, it’s used to form the future tense, translating to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "in" or "into" in English, indicating location or direction.</div><div><strong>der Achterbahn</strong> This phrase translates to "the roller coaster". "Der Achterbahn" is a feminine noun in the dative case following the preposition "in" (which can require dative or accusative depending on whether it describes a stationary location or a direction; here, it suggests a stationary location).</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It negates the statement that follows.</div><div><strong>schreien</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to scream" or "to shout". Being in the infinitive form, it complements "werde" to form the future tense construction, translating into English as "will not scream".</div>','<h2>Wie viel Milch mögen Sie in Ihrem Kaffee?</h2><div><strong>Wie viel</strong> These German words mean "how much". It is used to ask about the quantity or amount of something.</div><div><strong>Milch</strong> This is the German word for "milk". It’s a noun in the accusative case because it’s the direct object of the sentence—the thing being liked.</div><div><strong>mögen</strong> This is the German verb that means "to like" or "to prefer". It’s in the second-person plural formal or third-person plural present tense form, which is "Sie" in this sentence, indicating a formal address to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal version of "you" in German. It can refer to one or several persons in a formal context and is used both as the subject and the polite address form.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a German preposition that, in this context, denotes where the milk should be placed. It’s used to indicate location and is followed by the dative case.</div><div><strong>Ihrem</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "Ihr" in the dative case, masculine or neuter, and denotes ownership. In this sentence, it’s "your" referring to something that belongs to the person being addressed formally.</div><div><strong>Kaffee?</strong> This is the German word for "coffee". It’s a masculine noun and is in the dative case following the preposition "in".</div>','<h2>Sie haben also den Raubüberfall in der Bank gesehen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. When capitalized, it can also be the formal second-person singular or plural, equivalent to "you". In this sentence, "Sie" probably refers to a formal "you" addressing one or more persons.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the third-person plural or formal second-person present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this context, it’s used to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>also</strong> This is an adverb in German meaning "therefore", "so", or "thus". It’s used here to connect to a previous statement or context.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in the accusative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to indicate a specific object that follows, which is "Raubüberfall".</div><div><strong>Raubüberfall</strong> This is a German noun meaning "robbery" or "hold-up". It’s in the singular form and the masculine gender. Here, it’s the direct object of the sentence, denoting what was seen.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German which can mean "in" or "inside". It governs both the dative and the accusative case, depending on the context of movement or location. Here, it indicates the location where the robbery occurred.</div><div><strong>der Bank</strong> This phrase combines the feminine singular definite article in the dative case, "der", with the noun "Bank", which means "bank" in English. Due to the preposition "in", which implies location here, it takes the dative case, thus "in der Bank" means "in the bank".</div><div><strong>gesehen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "sehen", which means "to see". In the present perfect tense, it’s combined with "haben" to indicate that the action has been completed in the past. Therefore, "haben ... gesehen" translates to "have seen".</div>','<h2>Das Kind sitzt auf dem Stuhl.</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is the definite article for neutral nouns in the nominative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It indicates a specific noun is being referred to.</div><div><strong>Kind</strong> This is a neutral noun in German that means "child". In this sentence, it acts as the subject, which is the person performing the action of sitting.</div><div><strong>sitzt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sitzen", which means "to sit". It describes the action the subject (the child) is performing.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German that can have various meanings depending on the context. In this case, it means "on" indicating the position of the subject.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the definite article for masculine or neuter nouns in the dative case in German. It is used here with "Stuhl" (chair) because the preposition "auf" requires the dative case when indicating a location where something is at rest.</div><div><strong>Stuhl</strong> This is a masculine noun that means "chair". In this sentence, it takes the dative case due to the preposition "auf", and it serves as the indirect object, indicating where the child is sitting.</div>','<h2>Gehen Sie auf ein Date mit mir?</h2><div><strong>Gehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. In this context, it’s used to formally address one person.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition which, in this context, is part of the phrase "auf ein Date gehen", translating to "go on a date" in English.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the indefinite article in German, used here for the neuter noun "Date". It corresponds to "a" in English.</div><div><strong>Date</strong> This is a loanword from English used in German, which means "date" as in a romantic appointment or meeting.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition meaning "with" in English.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in the dative case in German, equivalent to "with me" in English when combined with the preposition "mit".</div>','<h2>Perfekt, das Taxi ist auf dem Weg.</h2><div><strong>Perfekt</strong> This is the German word for "perfect". It expresses satisfaction or approval. In this case, it conveys that something is as desired or that a situation is ideal.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neutral definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. In this sentence, it is used before the noun "Taxi" to signify a specific taxi is being referred to.</div><div><strong>Taxi</strong> Borrowed from English, "Taxi" is a common noun in German meaning "taxi" or "cab". It is the subject of the sentence and refers to the vehicle for hire.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "das Taxi" to its current state or condition.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a German preposition that, in this context, means "on" or "on the way". It is part of the prepositional phrase "auf dem Weg" and describes the motion or progress of the taxi.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the dative definite article for neuter or masculine nouns in German, equivalent to "the" in English. Here, it precedes "Weg" as part of the prepositional phrase.</div><div><strong>Weg</strong> This is a German noun meaning "way" or "path". In this sentence, "auf dem Weg" combined means "on the way" indicating that the taxi is en route or in the process of arriving.</div>','<h2>Das kommt auf das Röntgenergebnis an.</h2><div><strong>Das</strong> This is a neuter definite article in German, translating to "the" in English. It’s used here to refer to a specific thing or situation.</div><div><strong>kommt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come". In this context, it’s part of the expression "es kommt darauf an", meaning "it depends on".</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This preposition translates to "on" in English, and is used here as part of the phrase "es kommt darauf an", creating the meaning of dependency or reliance on something.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is again the neuter definite article in German, translating to "the" in English. It’s repeated here because it is referring to a specific noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Röntgenergebnis</strong> This is a compound noun in German. "Röntgen" refers to "X-ray" (named after Wilhelm Röntgen, the discoverer of X-rays) and "Ergebnis" means "result". Combined, it means "X-ray result" or "the result of an X-ray".</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is the third word in the phrase "es kommt darauf an", which translates to "it depends on". Although it’s often separated from "darauf" in English ("it depends on"), in German, "an" is separated from "darauf" by the noun phrase "das Röntgenergebnis". This structure emphasizes what the situation depends on.</div>','<h2>Es gibt nichts auf dem Tisch.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is often used as a dummy subject in existential sentences—sentences that state the existence or non-existence of something.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give". In this context, it is used to express that there is something (or nothing) somewhere, functioning similarly to "there is" or "there are" in English.</div><div><strong>nichts</strong> This is a pronoun in German meaning "nothing". It negates the existence of anything specific and is the direct object of the verb in this sentence.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German that can be translated to "on" in English. It describes the location of something in relation to a surface or area.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the masculine or neuter definite article in the dative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes "Tisch" to indicate a specific table.</div><div><strong>Tisch</strong> This is a masculine noun in German which means "table". In this sentence, it is in the dative case due to the preposition "auf", which requires the dative when indicating a location where something remains static or not moving (as opposed to a movement towards something).</div>','<h2>Sie hasst es, auf das Eis zu fallen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hasst</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "hassen", which means "to hate". It indicates the action or feeling of the subject.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. Here, it serves as an anticipatory object referring to the action of falling on the ice.</div><div><strong>auf das Eis</strong> This phrase means "onto the ice". "Auf" is a preposition that indicates direction or location, combined with the article "das" (the) and "Eis" (ice), it refers to the surface on which the action is taking place.</div><div><strong>zu fallen</strong> This is an infinitive construction with "zu" equivalent to "to fall" in English. It describes the action that the subject hates, forming part of the object of the sentence that "es" refers to.</div>','<h2>Ihr legt Besteck auf den Tisch.</h2></div><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person informally.</div><div><strong>legt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "legen", which means "to place" or "to put". It indicates what the subject is doing in the sentence.</div><div><strong>Besteck</strong> This is a German noun meaning "cutlery" or "silverware". In this sentence, it is the direct object, indicating what is being placed.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a German preposition that can have several meanings, but in this context, it translates to "on" in English, indicating the placement of the cutlery.</div><div><strong>den Tisch</strong> This phrase is composed of the article "den" (the accusative masculine form of "the") and the noun "Tisch", which means "table". Together, "den Tisch" means "the table", and it is the indirect object in this sentence, indicating where the cutlery is being placed.</div>','<h2>Ihr sprangt auf dem Trampolin.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sprangt</strong> This is the second-person plural past tense form of the verb "springen", which means "to jump". It describes the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>auf dem</strong> This is a prepositional phrase combining "auf", a preposition meaning "on", with the dative article "dem", meaning "the". "Auf dem" indicates the location where the jumping took place.</div><div><strong>Trampolin</strong> This is a German noun meaning "trampoline". It is neutral gender and in the dative case due to the preposition "auf" (when it is used to describe a location where something is happening).</div>','<h2>Eure Schlüssel liegen auf dem Boden.</h2><div><strong>Eure</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German for "your" in the plural form. It indicates that the keys belong to a group being spoken to, which could be two or more people.</div><div><strong>Schlüssel</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun for "key". In this sentence, it is the subject.</div><div><strong>liegen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "liegen", which means "to lie" or "to be situated". It describes the position of the keys.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German which means "on" in English. It indicates the position in relation to another object.</div><div><strong>dem</strong> This is the singular dative definite article "the" in English. In German, "dem" is used before masculine and neuter nouns in the dative case.</div><div><strong>Boden</strong> This is the singular form of the German noun for "floor" or "ground". In this sentence, it is in the dative case following the preposition "auf".</div>','<h2>Sie liest ein Magazin auf dem Sofa.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>liest</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "lesen", which means "to read". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>ein Magazin</strong> This phrase comprises an indefinite article "ein" (equivalent to "a" in English) and the noun "Magazin", which means "magazine". Together, this phrase is the direct object of the sentence, indicating what is being read.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German that can translate to "on" in English. It gives information about the location relative to another object, in this case, the sofa.</div><div><strong>dem Sofa</strong> This is a noun phrase consisting of the definite article "dem" (dative case of "the" in English, for neutral gender) and the noun "Sofa", which means "sofa". In German, "Sofa" is neutral, and "dem" denotes that the prepositional phrase is in the dative case, which is used here because of the preposition "auf" (when it implies a static position).</div>','<h2>Wir haben ein Sonderangebot auf alle Matratzen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It denotes possession or refers to actions like "have" in the context of "having something on offer".</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, which corresponds to "a" or "an" in English. It is used here with a neuter noun.</div><div><strong>Sonderangebot</strong> This is a noun in German, which means "special offer" or "sale". It is the direct object of the sentence, referring to the special deal being offered.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a preposition in German that can have various meanings depending on the context. In this sentence, it means "on" and is used to indicate the promotion is applicable to the object that follows.</div><div><strong>alle</strong> This is the plural form of the indefinite numeral "all" in German, and it is used here to refer to all items within a certain category, which is "mattresses" in this case.</div><div><strong>Matratzen</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Matratze", which means "mattresses" in English. It relates to the objects that the special offer applies to.</div>','<h2>Sie hat ihm einen Kuss auf die Wange gegeben.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for the third-person singular feminine, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it forms part of the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>ihm</strong> This is the third-person singular masculine dative pronoun in German, equivalent to "him" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the sentence, the person receiving the kiss.</div><div><strong>einen Kuss</strong> This phrase consists of an indefinite article "einen" (an/one) and the noun "Kuss", which means "a kiss" in English. This is the direct object of the sentence, representing what she gave.</div><div><strong>auf die Wange</strong> This prepositional phrase means "on the cheek" in English. "Auf" is the preposition "on", and "die Wange" is the singular accusative form of the noun "Wange", which means "cheek".</div><div><strong>gegeben</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "geben", which means "to give" in English. It is used here with the auxiliary verb "hat" to form the past perfect tense of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Es ist schwierig, auf das Eis zu klettern.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it". It functions as a dummy subject in this sentence, similar to how "it" is used in the English sentence "It is raining".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "es" with the predicative adjective "schwierig".</div><div><strong>schwierig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "difficult" or "hard". In this sentence, it describes the nature of the action.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a German preposition that can mean "on", "onto" or "to" depending on the context. Here, it is used with the accusative case to express direction towards a surface, indicating the action of climbing onto the ice.</div><div><strong>das Eis</strong> This is a combination of the definite article "das" (the) and "Eis" (ice), in the neuter gender and nominative or accusative singular. It’s the object that the action of climbing is being directed towards.</div><div><strong>zu klettern</strong> This verb phrase is the infinitive form of "klettern", which means "to climb". The word "zu" is used similarly to the English "to" in the infinitive, and the phrase functions as an infinitive construction here, connected to the main clause by the comma.</div>','<h2>Wir haben sehr hart an diesem Projekt gearbeitet.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the German pronoun for "we". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the auxiliary verb in the present perfect tense, which means "have". It’s used here to form the present perfect tense with the past participle of the main verb.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It’s used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>hart</strong> This is an adjective meaning "hard" in English. When used with "haben" in this context, it functions as an adverb modifying the verb "gearbeitet", describing the manner of the work.</div><div><strong>an diesem</strong> This is a prepositional phrase combining the preposition "an",, meaning "on" or "at", with the demonstrative pronoun "diesem", meaning "this". It sets the reference to "this project".</div><div><strong>Projekt</strong> This is a German noun meaning "project". It is the object of the preposition "an" and represents what the subject "we" have been working on.</div><div><strong>gearbeitet</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "arbeiten", which means "to work". It completes the present perfect tense along with the auxiliary verb "haben", indicating the action that was performed.</div>','<h2>Meine Hunde laufen weg, wenn sie nicht an der Leine sind.</h2><div><strong>Meine</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "my" in the plural form in German, indicating ownership of more than one item (in this case, dogs).</div><div><strong>Hunde</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Hund", which means "dog". It is the object being possessed as indicated by "meine".</div><div><strong>laufen</strong> This is the plural third-person present tense form of the verb "laufen", which means "to run" or "to walk". Here it indicates the action the dogs are performing.</div><div><strong>weg</strong> This is an adverb meaning "away". It modifies the verb "laufen" to indicate that the dogs are running away, not just running.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction meaning "when" or "if". It introduces the conditional clause in the sentence.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun "they" in German. It refers back to "Hunde" (the dogs).</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is an adverb meaning "not". It negates the following phrase to indicate the absence of something, in this case, "an der Leine".</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a preposition which can have several meanings depending on context. Here, combined with "der", it forms part of a prepositional phrase meaning "on the leash".</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article "the" in the feminine or plural dative case. It is used with the preposition "an" to form a prepositional phrase.</div><div><strong>Leine</strong> This is the German noun for "leash", and here it is used in the singular and dative case due to the preceding preposition "an der".</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the plural third-person present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It serves as the linking verb in the conditional clause.</div>','<h2>Er schlief an seinem Schreibtisch, weil er zu viel arbeitete.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>schlief</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "schlafen", which means "to sleep". It indicates the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "at", "on", or "by", depending on the context. In this sentence, it is part of a prepositional phrase indicating the location.</div><div><strong>seinem</strong> This is the dative form of the possessive pronoun "sein", equivalent to "his" in English. It modifies "Schreibtisch", agreeing in case, number, and gender.</div><div><strong>Schreibtisch,</strong> This is a masculine noun in German, meaning "desk". The comma indicates the end of the first clause before moving on to the clause that provides the reason for the action.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It introduces a clause explaining the reason or cause.</div><div><strong>er</strong> Again, this is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause introduced by "weil".</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is an adverb that modifies "viel", usually meaning "too" in this context, indicating excessiveness.</div><div><strong>viel</strong> This is an adjective that means "much" or "a lot". Here it’s used with "arbeitete" to indicate the extent of the action.</div><div><strong>arbeitete.</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "arbeiten", which means "to work". It is the verb in the subordinate clause, describing the action the subject performed excessively.</div>','<h2>Sie können an der Kasse zahlen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, which can refer to one person in a formal setting or to several people. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>können</strong> This is a modal verb meaning "can" or "to be able to". It indicates the possibility or ability to perform an action.</div><div><strong>an der Kasse</strong> This phrase means "at the cash register". "An" is a preposition which means "at", "der" is the definite article "the" in dative case (due to the preposition "an" requiring dative here), and "Kasse" means "cash register" or "checkout".</div><div><strong>zahlen</strong> This is the verb "to pay" in its infinitive form, indicating the action being performed by the subject.</div>','<h2>Ja, an dieselbe Adresse, bitte.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It is often used to affirm or agree with something that has been asked or stated previously.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a German preposition that means "to" or "at" when describing a direction or location. It is often used with accusative or dative case depending on the context.</div><div><strong>dieselbe</strong> This is the inflected form of the German demonstrative pronoun "derselbe", which means "the same". The ending "-elbe" corresponds to the feminine/neuter accusative case here, indicating that it is pointing to a feminine or neuter noun in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Adresse</strong> This is a German noun meaning "address". In this sentence, it is in the accusative case as it is the direct object of the preposition "an".</div><div><strong>bitte</strong> This is a German word that is used as a polite form of request or to say "please". It is often used at the end of a sentence to make the request sound more polite.</div>','<h2>Sie haben beim Camping an diesem Wochenende Spaß gehabt.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the plural form of "you" in German and it is also the formal version of the singular "you". It’s both the subject and nominative case.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the auxiliary verb "to have" in the third-person plural present tense. It is used here to form the past tense (Perfekt) together with the participle.</div><div><strong>beim</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "bei" and the definite article "dem", which together mean "at the" or "during the". It indicates the location or activity related to the main verb.</div><div><strong>Camping</strong> This is a German noun derived from English, meaning "camping". It acts as the noun complement of the preposition "bei" and is in dative case due to the preposition.</div><div><strong>an diesem</strong> This is a temporal phrase consisting of "an", a preposition that can mean "on", "at", "in", etc., depending on context, combined with "diesem", the demonstrative pronoun "this" in the dative case, neutral gender. It indicates a specific time, "this" weekend.</div><div><strong>Wochenende</strong> This is a German noun meaning "weekend". It is the time frame being referred to, and is in the dative case following the preposition "an".</div><div><strong>Spaß</strong> This is a German noun meaning "fun". In this sentence, it is an object that reflects what they had.</div><div><strong>gehabt</strong> This is the past participle of "haben" and it’s used here to complete the Perfekt tense construction, indicating a completed action in the past.</div>','<h2>Passieren: Was passierte an deinem Geburtstag?</h2><div><strong>Passieren</strong> This is the German verb that means "to happen" or "to occur". It’s used here in the infinitive form as the title of the sentence breakdown.</div><div><strong>Was</strong> This is the German interrogative pronoun meaning "what". It is used here to ask about the nature of the event or occurrence.</div><div><strong>passierte</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "passieren". It indicates something that happened or took place in the past.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a German preposition which can mean "on", "at", or "in" depending on the context. In this sentence, it is used with the dative case to mean "on" (referring to a date or time).</div><div><strong>deinem</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "dein" in the dative masculine/neuter singular form, and it means "your". It implies ownership or relation to the subject of the sentence, who is the person addressed.</div><div><strong>Geburtstag</strong> This is a German noun meaning "birthday". It’s in the dative case because it follows the preposition "an", which in this context means "on" (referring to a specific day).</div>','<h2>Frau Müller ist die schlechteste Lehrerin an der Schule.</h2><div><strong>Frau</strong> This is a German title used for a woman, equivalent to "Mrs". or "Ms". in English, preceding a family name.</div><div><strong>Müller</strong> This is a common German surname. In the context of this sentence, this name follows the title "Frau", indicating the person’s identity.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It connects the subject of the sentence, "Frau Müller", with the predicate adjective.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the feminine definite article in German, used here for the feminine noun "Lehrerin". It means "the" in English.</div><div><strong>schlechteste</strong> This is a superlative adjective in German, derived from "schlecht" meaning "bad", which translates to "the worst" in English. It qualifies the noun "Lehrerin" to indicate the degree of comparison.</div><div><strong>Lehrerin</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that means "teacher". It refers to the profession of the subject Frau Müller.</div><div><strong>an</strong> This is a preposition in German that often indicates location or presence in a particular place, comparable to "at" in English.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the feminine definite article in the dative case in German, used here because of the preposition "an". It also means "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Schule</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that means "school", representing the place where Frau Müller works as a teacher.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);